{
  "text": "It is of course not an entirely modern occurrence to gloss jing as a physical object (whether 'the body' or 'gametes')-this has a historical basis in its alternative identity as semen. Whilst it is impossible to verify how the pre-Han originators of CM conceived of jing, one might imagine that despite their 135 [CITATION_1] primary focus on process, resonance, and relationship, 144 they still had to somehow classify the physical 'stuff ' of the human body-physicality that visibly suffered inexorable temporal decline, with an associated deterioration in reproductive capacity. It may be that jing fitted as a descriptor of the 'body' in this regard.",
